  <h1>Forthglade vs Wainwright's Wet Dog Food — Premium vs Supermarket Value</h1>

  <p class="meta" style="color: var(--color-text-light); margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">
    Last updated: June 2026 · 10 min read
  </p>

  <p>If you want a grain-free, hypoallergenic <strong>wet</strong> dog food in the UK but don't want to spend Canagan or Nature's Menu money, two brands keep coming up: <strong>Forthglade</strong> and <strong>Wainwright's</strong>. They look similar on the shelf — both British-made, grain-free, single-source-protein trays — but they sit at opposite ends of the price ladder. Forthglade is the premium Devon boutique; Wainwright's is Pets at Home's value own-brand. This is the classic <strong>quality-per-£</strong> decision.</p>

  <p>The short version: <strong>Forthglade</strong> is the higher-quality can — more meat, a top-tier independent rating, fuller transparency — at a premium price. <strong>Wainwright's</strong> delivers most of the grain-free, hypoallergenic benefit for roughly half the cost, if you shop at Pets at Home. This guide compares them head-to-head on meat content, ingredients, independent ratings, price and availability — informed by feeding our own dog, <strong>Milo, a 12-year-old Labrador/Lurcher rescue who's wheat-sensitive</strong>, alongside published data and independent All About Dog Food (AADF) ratings.</p>

