  <h2>Meat Content & Ingredients</h2>

  <p>Both brands share the same hypoallergenic philosophy: a single named protein, no added wheat, pork, dairy or soya, and no artificial flavours, colours or preservatives — exactly the recipe you want for a sensitive dog. The difference is how much meat goes in and how openly it's declared.</p>

  <p><strong>Forthglade</strong> leads on meat. Its grain-free complete wet trays are built on <strong>75% single-source protein</strong> (salmon, lamb, duck, beef or turkey), gently steamed in Devon, with vegetables and botanicals and no fillers. The single-source recipes make it a genuinely strong option for elimination diets, and the brand publishes its ingredient breakdown clearly. Forthglade has been <strong>voted Best Wet Food by <em>Your Dog Magazine</em> readers several years running</strong>.</p>

  <p><strong>Wainwright's</strong> uses the same <strong>single-source, hypoallergenic</strong> formula — turkey, lamb, duck or white fish with vegetables, UK-made, no added wheat/pork/dairy/soya or artificial additives. But the meat percentage is lower and isn't headlined the way Forthglade's is, and as an own-brand range it offers less ingredient transparency than a boutique. One practical note: Wainwright's grain-free recipes are produced in a factory that also handles grain, so it's grain-<em>free recipe</em> rather than guaranteed grain-zero — worth knowing for the most severely intolerant dogs.</p>

  <p><strong>Verdict:</strong> Forthglade for higher meat content and full transparency; Wainwright's for the same hypoallergenic basics at a lower spec and price.</p>

  <h2>Independent Ratings</h2>

  <p>On the independent <strong>All About Dog Food</strong> scale — the UK's most trusted neutral rating — the gap is clear. <strong>Forthglade's grain-free complete wet rates around 77–82% depending on recipe</strong>, putting it among the best-scoring wet foods on the site thanks to its high single-source meat and clean ingredient list. <strong>Wainwright's grain-free wet sits in the solid mid-band</strong> — comfortably above typical supermarket cans and a genuinely respectable score for a value own-brand, but a step below Forthglade. Both are naturally preserved and certified complete to FEDIAF standards; you're paying for that rating difference.</p>

  <p><strong>Verdict:</strong> Forthglade by a clear margin on independent rating — though Wainwright's punches above its price.</p>

  <h2>Cost & Availability</h2>

  <p>This is where Wainwright's makes its case. Its grain-free 395g trays are around <strong>£1.61–1.80</strong> each (cheapest on Pets at Home Easy Repeat), and a <strong>6-can variety pack runs about £10.79–11.99</strong> — roughly £1.80/can. <strong>Forthglade's</strong> 395g grain-free trays carry a single-tray RRP nearer <strong>£1.80–2.20+</strong>, only dropping toward <strong>£1.26–1.48</strong> when you commit to a larger multi-tray subscription. For an everyday shop without locking into a big subscription, Wainwright's is usually the cheaper grain-free wet — that's exactly what it's designed to be.</p>

  <p>Availability cuts the other way. <strong>Wainwright's is Pets at Home own-brand</strong>, so it's only sold through Pets at Home (in store, online and via Easy Repeat) — convenient if you have a branch nearby, restrictive if you don't. <strong>Forthglade</strong> is more widely stocked: its own website, pet shops, online retailers and some supermarkets, so you're not tied to a single chain.</p>

  <p><strong>Verdict:</strong> Wainwright's for everyday value (if you shop at Pets at Home); Forthglade for the best subscription price and wider availability.</p>

  <h2>Quality-per-£: Which Gives You More?</h2>

  <p>This is the real question with a premium-vs-value matchup. Pound for pound, <strong>Forthglade</strong> gives you more meat, a higher AADF rating and more transparency — but you pay for it, especially at single-tray prices. <strong>Wainwright's</strong> gives up some meat content and a few rating points but delivers the core grain-free, hypoallergenic, single-source benefit for roughly half the cost. For a healthy dog, that's outstanding value; for a fussy, senior or genuinely sensitive dog, Forthglade's extra quality can justify the premium.</p>

  <p>For our own <strong>Milo (12)</strong>, who's wheat-sensitive, single-source grain-free wet from either brand sits well — the moisture and aroma help a fading senior appetite, and neither triggers his sensitivities. For a fuller breakdown of feeding older dogs, see our <a href="/best-senior-dog-food-uk/">best senior dog food guide</a>.</p>

  <p><strong>Verdict:</strong> Forthglade wins on absolute quality; Wainwright's wins on value-for-money. Both clear the supermarket-can bar easily.</p>

  <h2>Which Should You Choose?</h2>

  <p>There's no single winner — it depends on your priorities and your dog:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Choose Forthglade if:</strong> you want the highest-quality grain-free wet — more meat, a top AADF rating, full transparency — and you'll pay a premium or subscribe for the best per-tray price. Ideal for fussy, sensitive or senior dogs.</li>
    <li><strong>Choose Wainwright's if:</strong> value matters most, you shop at Pets at Home, or you're feeding multiple dogs and want a genuinely good grain-free, hypoallergenic wet without the boutique price.</li>
    <li><strong>Want more meat or novel proteins?</strong> Step up to Nature's Menu Country Hunter (80% meat) or Canagan (joint support) — see our full roundup.</li>
    <li><strong>Still unsure?</strong> Buy a few trays of each and let your dog decide — palatability is individual, and both are safe, complete grain-free options.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>For the wider field — including how Forthglade earns our top pick and where Wainwright's lands as best value — see our full <a href="/best-grain-free-wet-dog-food-uk/">best grain-free wet dog food UK guide</a>. And for the premium-brand-vs-supermarket-convenience angle, see <a href="/canagan-vs-lilys-kitchen-wet/">Canagan vs Lily's Kitchen</a>.</p>

  <h2>How to Switch</h2>

  <p>Whichever you choose, transition gradually over <strong>7-10 days</strong>, mixing increasing amounts of the new food into the old. Wet food is richer and more moisture-dense than kibble, so a sudden switch can cause loose stools — slow down if you see any upset. As always, if your dog's appetite, weight or toileting changes noticeably and doesn't settle, book a vet check.</p>

